{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"Included with: <b> ὀξύς</b>, εῖα, ύ, <br /> <i>Ionic dialect</i> <i>feminine</i> ὀξέα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.23, +others, variant in 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “γυναικεῖα” 1.64, +others (in codices frequently ὀξέη, and so 2nd c.AD: Babrius Fabularum Scriptor 73.1 for the sake of meter): ὀξεῖα, poetry for _neuter_ _plural_ ὀξέα, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 348 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>sharp, keen,</b> whether of a point or an edge, in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus and 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] mostly of weapons or anything made of metal, ἄκων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.335, +others; ἄορ 21.173, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 457; βέλος 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.185, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also of non-metallic substances, λᾶας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.739; μοχλός 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.382; σκόλοπες 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.56, 64 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὀξεῖα κορυφή, of a mountain-peak, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.74; so πάγοι ὀξέες 5.411 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; λίθος ὀξὺς πεποιημένος <b>sharpened</b> so as to serve as a knife, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.69, compare 3.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κυρβασίας ἐς ὀξὺ ἀπηγμένας brought to a <b>point,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 7.64; ὄρεα ἐς ὀ. τὰς κορυφὰς ἀ. [prev. author] 2.28 \">Refs</a>]; τὸ ὀ. the <b>apex</b> of a triangle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 16 \">Refs</a>]; of the heart, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Respiratione” 478b5; τὸ ὀ. τοῦ ᾠοῦ [prev. author] “GA” 752b8 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὀ. γωνία an <b>acute</b> angle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Top.” 107a16, +others, 3rd c.BC: Euclides Geometra 1 “Def.” 12, 3rd c.BC: Archimedes Geometra “περὶ ἑλίκων” 16; Χρόνος ὀξὺς ὀδόντας 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 176 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ ὀξεῖα, name of a surgical instrument, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Hermes” 38.282, 1st-2nd c.AD: Heliodorus Medicus cited in 4th c.AD: Oribasius Medicus 44.23.59 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; but also, a <b>pointed splinter</b> of bone, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 46.20.5. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in reference to the senses, <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> of feeling, <b>sharp, keen,</b> ὀδύναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.268 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὀ. ἠέλιος the <b>piercing</b> sun, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Apollinem” 374 \">Refs</a>]; ὀξειᾶν ἀκτίνων πατήρ, i.e. the Sun, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.70; Σείριος ὀξὺς ἐλλάμπων 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 61; πῦρ ὀ. 4th c.BC: Anaxippus Comicus 1.12; so χιὼν ὀξεῖα 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.20 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; so also of grief and the like, ἄχος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.125; μελεδῶναι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.517 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: and generally, <b>sharp, severe,</b> μάχη ὀξέα.. γίνεται <b>keenly contested,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.23; ὀ. πυρετός 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἀρχαίης ἰητρικῇς” 16 (_superlative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; [ἡ νόσος] ὀξεῖα φοιτᾷ καὶ ταχεῖ᾽ ἀπέρχεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 808 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νόσοι, μανίαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 8.85, “N.” 11.48 (_comparative_),compare 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “Acut.” at Title Page, 2nd c.AD: Archigenes Medicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 9.887; πάθαι 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 3.97; ἐπιμομφά [prev. author] “O.” 10(11).9, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> of the sight, ὀξύτατον ὄμμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “N.” 10.62; ὄψις.. ὀξυτάτη τῶν διὰ τοῦ σώματος.. αἰσθήσεων 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 250d: frequently in _neuter_ as \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i>, ὀξύτατον δέρκεσθαι to be <b>keenest</b> of sight, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.675; ὀξύτατα καθορᾶν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 516c \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; so ὀξὺ νοεῖν notice a thing <b>sharply,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.374; ὀξὺ προϊδεῖν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.393; ὀξύτερον βλέπει 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 1048, “Lys.” 1202 (Lyric poetry): proverbial, ὀξύτερον τοῦ Λυγκέως βλέπειν [prev. author] “Pl.” 210, compare 15th c.AD: Macarius Paroemiographus “Prov.” 6.41 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also ὀξὺ ἄκουσεν heard <b>with sharp ear,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.256, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 927b \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὀξεῖαν ἀκοὴν.. λόγοις διδούς <b>keen</b> attention, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 30. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.2.b</b></Level4> of things that affect the sight, <b>dazzling, bright,</b> αὐγὴ Ἠελίου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.372; [Ἠελίου] ὀξύτατον πέλεται φάος εἰσοράασθαι 14.345 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: hence of colours, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 1173 (see. φοινικίς 2); αἱ ὀξεῖαι χροιαί 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Physiognomonica” 806b4; πορφύρα 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Cat.Mi.” 6, “PHolm.” 20.36; [ἐσθὴς] ὀξυτέρα καὶ τηλαυγεστέρα 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 4.46. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> of sound, <b>shrill, piercing,</b> ἀϋτή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.313; ὀξὺ βοήσας 17.89; ὀξὺ δὲ κωκύσασα 18.71; ὀξὺ λεληκώς 22.141; ὀξέα κεκληγώς 17.88, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of whinnying horses, ὀξεῖα χρέμισαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 348 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of young pigs, ὀξὺ κεκράγατε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 804 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the scream of birds of prey, ὀξέα κλάζων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 112 (_anapaest meter_) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of metals, ἰάχεσκε σάκος ὀξέα καὶ λιγέως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 233 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also of the wail of the nightingale (compare ὀξύφωνος), ὄρνιθος ὀ. φθόγγον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 424 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so ἐπηλάλαξαν τὸν ὀ. νόμον shrieked their <b>shrill</b> song, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 952 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὀξὺ μέλος, of the grasshopper, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1095 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.3.b</b></Level4> of musical tones, in a technical sense, <b>high-pitched,</b> opposed to βαρύς, φθόγγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 80a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 6.20; ὀξυτάτη χορδή 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 268d; φωνὴ ὀξεῖα, βαρεῖα, μέση 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1403b29; τῷ ὀξεῖ ἐν φωνῇ μὲν ἐναντίον τὸ βαρύ, ἐν ὄγκῳ δὲ τὸ ἀμβλύ [prev. author] “Top.” 106a13. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.3.c</b></Level4> in Music, δι᾽ ὀξειῶν (<i>Doric dialect</i> -ᾶν) <b>interval of a fifth,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Philolaus Philosophus 6, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 920a24. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.3.d</b></Level4> ἡ ὀξεῖα (i.e. προσῳδία) the <b>acute</b> accent, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Dionysius Thrax Grammaticus 630.1, 2nd c.AD: Apollonius Dyscolus Grammaticus “de Pronominibus;” 35.10, +others\">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]; τὸν τόνον φυλάσσειν ὀ.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 60.1; ὀ. συλλαβή 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 399b; ὀ. στοιχεῖον 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “adversus Mathematicos” 1.113. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> of taste, <b>sharp, pungent, acid,</b> φακῆ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 6.2.31; ὄξος 4th-3rd c.BC: Diphilus Comicus 18.1; οἶνος 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 141.12; ἐξ ὀξέος καὶ ἁλμυροῦ ξυνθεὶς ζύμωμα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 74c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.5</b></Level3> of smell, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Anima” 421a30; ὀξύτατον ὄζειν τινός 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 193. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i>, of the inner sense, <b>sharp, keen, hasty,</b> especially <b>quick to anger, passionate,</b> epithet of Ares, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.440, +others; μένος ὀξύ “Hymni Homerici” 8.14; καρδίη ὀξυτέρη 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 366; θυμὸς ὀ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1193; νέος καὶ ὀ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 463e; οἱ ἀκρόχολοι ὀξεῖς 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1126a18: so in ὀξύ-θυμος, -κάρδιος, -χολος. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <b>sharp, quick,</b> δεινοὶ καὶ ὀξεῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 39b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, ἐπινοῆσαι ὀ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.70; γνῶναι.. ὀξύτατοι τὰ ῥηθέντα 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 3.15; also εἰς πάντα τὰ μαθήματα ὀξεῖς 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 526b; τὰς ἐνθυμήσεις ὀξύς 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Salt.” 81. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> of motion, <b>quick, swift,</b> post-[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, ὀξυτάτους ἵππους 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.9 (variant{ὠκυτάτους}) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἱερακίσκος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1112; ὀξυτέρῳ χαλινῷ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 108 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a report, ὀξεῖα βάξις διῆλθ᾽ Ἀχαιούς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Aj.” 998 \">Refs</a>]; ὀξεῖαν ἐκβάλλει ῥοήν, of a dying man, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 1238, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1389 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; of a flame, <b>fierce,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 5.9.3; ᾄξας ὀξὺς νότος ὥς 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 258 (_anapaest meter_) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ εὔψυχον.. ὀξεῖς ἐνδείκνυνται are <b>quick</b> in displaying, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.126 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to βραδύς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 8.96 \">Refs</a>]; opposed to ῥάθυμος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Eudemia” 1240a2 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ἡσύχιος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “EN” 1116a9; ὀ. παράγγελμα 1st c.AD: Onosander (Onasander) Tacticus 10.2 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; ὀ. καιρός an <b>urgent</b> crisis, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 6.1, +others\">Refs</a>]; ὁ ὀ. δρόμος the <b>express</b> post, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “POxy.” 900.7 (4th c.AD), 2115.6 (4th c.AD) \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]; ὀξεῖς οἱ πόδες αὐτῶν ἐκχέαι αἷμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Rom.3.15: especially in \">NT</a>] <i>adverb</i> (see. below). <br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> regular <i>adverb</i> <u>ὀξέως</u> <b>quickly, soon,</b> βοηθεῖν, μεταχειρίσαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.10, 12, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>sharply,</b> ὁρᾶν, αἰσθάνεσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 567b, “Phdr.” 263c; poetry ὀξείως “epigram Gr.” 986.3 (from Philae)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>comparative</i> ὀξυτέρως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιδημίαι” 3.17.β; ὀξυτέρως ἀποθῄνσκειν [prev. work] 1.2 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but, <br /><Level3><b>__V.2</b></Level3> <i>neuter</i> ὀξύ and <i>plural</i> ὀξέα as <i>adverb</i>, see above [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.2, 3: _comparative_ ὀξύτερον 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.8, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 190a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>superlative</i> ὀξύτατον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.675, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 741d; or ὀξύτατα [prev. author] “R.” 401e, +others (Cf. ὀξίνα, ὄκρις.) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8525","accentedUnicode":"ὀξέως","shortDef":"swiftly","mediumDef":"swiftly","stepGloss":"swiftly","stepTransliteration":"oxeōs","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}